        <p class="eyebrow mb-2">Definition</p>
        <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed text-ink-200">
          <strong class="text-[var(--accent)]">Google Search Generative Experience (SGE)</strong> was Google's experimental AI search feature,
          available via Search Labs from May 2023. It placed AI-generated answers above organic search results. The feature launched at
          general availability in May 2024 under the name <strong class="text-white">Google AI Overviews</strong>,
          which is the current production product name.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 1: What Was SGE -->
      <section id="what-was-sge" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What Was Google SGE (Search Generative Experience)?</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Google SGE, formally named Search Generative Experience, was an experimental AI search feature that Google made available to opt-in users through its Search Labs programme beginning in May 2023.</strong>
          It was the first public demonstration of Google integrating a large language model directly into the core Search results page.
        </p>

        <p>
          SGE appeared as an AI-generated panel at the top of the search results page for certain query types. The panel displayed a
          synthesised text answer, typically accompanied by three to five suggested follow-up questions, and showed a small carousel of
          source pages used to generate the response. Users could click the sources, expand them, or continue the conversation with
          follow-up queries in a conversational format.
        </p>

        <p>
          The experimental nature of SGE was significant. Because it was an opt-in feature accessible only to Search Labs participants,
          it did not affect the search experience for the vast majority of Google users. Marketers and SEOs who tested SGE during this
          period were observing a product that was explicitly in development and not representative of a finalised experience.
        </p>

        <p>
          Google used the SGE period to observe user behaviour, gather feedback, and refine both the technical architecture and the
          content policies governing which sources the AI would cite. Many of the early observations about SGE — which query types
          triggered it, how sources were selected, what content got cited — reflected a product that was intentionally unstable and
          subject to frequent, sometimes dramatic, changes.
        </p>

        <p>
          For the broader context of why this matters for AI search strategy, the
          <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation guide</a>
          covers the full landscape of AI search systems and how they differ from one another.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: SGE Timeline -->
      <section id="sge-timeline" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark mb-8">
          <h2>SGE Timeline: From Experiment to Product</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Understanding the SGE-to-AI Overviews timeline clarifies why much early SGE optimisation guidance is now outdated and why the terminology shift matters.</strong>
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card overflow-hidden mb-8">
          <div class="overflow-x-auto">
            <table class="w-full text-sm">
              <thead>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line)]">
                  <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3.5 text-left font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-ink-300">Date</th>
                  <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3.5 text-left font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-ink-300">Event</th>
                  <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3.5 text-left font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-ink-300">Significance</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody class="text-ink-200">
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-ink-300 whitespace-nowrap">May 2023</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">SGE announced at Google I/O</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">Search Labs opt-in experiment launched in the US; AI-generated answers above organic results for the first time</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-ink-300 whitespace-nowrap">2023–2024</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">SGE experiment phase</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">Feature tested with Search Labs users; frequent changes to query scope, source selection, and UI; limited to opt-in participants</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-ink-300 whitespace-nowrap">May 2024</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">AI Overviews launched at Google I/O</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">Feature renamed to AI Overviews, moved to general availability in the US, and removed from Search Labs requirement</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-ink-300 whitespace-nowrap">May–Jun 2024</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">Post-launch adjustments</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">Google significantly reduced AI Overview trigger rate after user feedback and high-profile inaccuracy examples; content policies tightened</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-ink-300 whitespace-nowrap">Late 2024</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">International expansion</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">AI Overviews rolled out to additional markets including the UK and selected European and Asian markets</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-ink-300 whitespace-nowrap">2025–2026</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100">Ongoing evolution</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">Continued expansion of query coverage, integration with Gemini model updates, and development of measurement tools for site owners</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark">
          <p>
            The timeline illustrates why advice from the SGE experiment phase should be treated with caution. The product changed
            substantially at the May 2024 launch, and then changed again in the weeks following launch as Google responded to feedback.
            Tactics that appeared to work during the Search Labs experiment were not always transferable to the production product.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: SGE to AI Overviews — What Changed -->
      <section id="sge-to-ai-overviews" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>SGE to AI Overviews: What Changed</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The transition from SGE to AI Overviews was not simply a name change — Google made substantive changes to query coverage, source selection, and content policies.</strong>
          Practitioners who built their understanding of the feature during the SGE phase need to account for these changes.
        </p>

        <h3>Query Coverage</h3>
        <p>
          SGE triggered for a wide range of queries during its experimental phase, including many queries where an AI-generated answer
          added minimal value over traditional search results. At the AI Overviews launch and in subsequent adjustments, Google narrowed
          the trigger criteria, focusing the feature on queries where synthesis genuinely improves the user experience. The overall
          trigger rate dropped notably in the weeks after the initial AI Overviews launch as Google refined this scope.
        </p>
        <p>
          The practical implication: a query that triggered SGE during the experiment phase may not trigger an AI Overview today,
          and vice versa. Query trigger analysis should always be based on the current production product.
        </p>

        <h3>Source Selection and Citations</h3>
        <p>
          SGE's source citation UI changed between the experimental and production phases. The experiment showed a small carousel of
          source pages; AI Overviews uses an expandable citations panel. More significantly, Google's approach to source selection
          evolved. The production product applies stricter E-E-A-T criteria and exhibits stronger correlation with traditional organic
          rankings than early SGE testing suggested.
        </p>

        <h3>Content Policy and YMYL Handling</h3>
        <p>
          Following high-profile examples of AI Overviews producing inaccurate or potentially harmful responses in the weeks after
          general availability, Google tightened its content policies for sensitive query types. Health, safety, finance, and legal
          queries now receive more conservative treatment — either suppressing AI Overviews entirely for certain sub-categories or
          applying stricter sourcing requirements. This represented a meaningful departure from SGE behaviour on similar queries.
        </p>

        <h3>Model Integration</h3>
        <p>
          SGE was built on an earlier generation of Google's AI models. AI Overviews is integrated with Google's Gemini model, which
          represents a different architecture and capability level. The quality of synthesis, the accuracy of attribution, and the
          range of query types handled well all changed with this transition. Early SGE observations about what content got cited
          and why may not generalise cleanly to Gemini-powered AI Overviews.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: Terminology Guide -->
      <section id="terminology" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark mb-8">
          <h2>Terminology Guide: SGE, AI Overviews, and Related Terms</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>The AI search space has accumulated multiple overlapping terms that are sometimes used interchangeably but refer to different things.</strong>
            This glossary clarifies the distinctions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4">

          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)] mb-2">Search Generative Experience (SGE)</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              The experimental name for Google's AI search feature, used from May 2023 to May 2024. SGE was an opt-in experiment
              available through Search Labs. The term is now deprecated — Google no longer uses it for the current production product.
              It remains common in industry content, particularly content written during the 2023–2024 period.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)] mb-2">Google AI Overviews</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              The current production name for Google's AI-generated answer feature in Search, launched at general availability in
              May 2024. This is the feature that practitioners and brands should be optimising for today. For current tactics,
              see our <a href="/google-ai-overview-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">Google AI Overview Optimisation guide</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)] mb-2">AI Overview Optimization / AI Overview Optimisation</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              The practice of structuring content, technical setup, and entity signals to earn inclusion as a cited source in
              Google AI Overviews. This is the current and correct framing for what was previously called SGE optimisation
              or search generative experience optimization.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)] mb-2">SGE Optimization / Search Generative Experience Optimization</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Older terminology for the same practice, coined during the SGE experiment phase. Still common in search queries
              because many practitioners first encountered the topic under the SGE label. Content using this term is often
              referring to the same set of practices now more accurately described as AI Overview optimisation — but may
              contain outdated tactical advice from the experiment period.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)] mb-2">Generative Engine Optimisation (GEO)</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              The broader discipline of optimising for AI-generated answers across all major AI search platforms — not only Google
              AI Overviews but also ChatGPT, Perplexity, Microsoft Copilot, and Gemini. GEO encompasses AI Overview optimisation
              as one component of a multi-platform strategy. For the full framework, see our
              <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO guide</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)] mb-2">Answer Engine Optimisation (AEO)</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              An adjacent discipline focused on getting content surfaced in direct-answer formats — featured snippets, Knowledge
              Panels, voice assistant responses. AEO predates the generative AI search era and focuses on different mechanisms,
              though there is significant structural overlap with GEO content requirements.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5: What SGE Optimisation Covered -->
      <section id="sge-optimisation-legacy" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What SGE Optimisation Covered — and What Carries Over</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Much of the guidance published under the "SGE optimisation" label during the 2023–2024 period contained accurate principles, even if some specific observations about the feature are now outdated.</strong>
          Here is what carries over and what does not.
        </p>

        <h3>What Carries Over to AI Overviews</h3>
        <p>
          The core principles that practitioners identified during SGE testing remain directionally correct for AI Overviews:
        </p>
        <ul>
