          <li><strong>Structured content is more extractable.</strong> Clear headings, declarative statements, and FAQ sections that facilitate passage-level extraction remained effective signals in the transition.</li>
          <li><strong>Structured data improves classification.</strong> FAQPage, HowTo, and Article schema continued to support accurate passage extraction after the product launch.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>What Does Not Carry Over from SGE</h3>
        <p>
          Some tactics and observations from the SGE period are no longer reliable guides:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Query trigger lists from SGE testing.</strong> The queries that triggered SGE during the experiment shifted substantially at launch and continued to evolve. Any specific list of "SGE-triggering queries" from before May 2024 is likely inaccurate for AI Overviews.</li>
          <li><strong>UI-based observations.</strong> SGE and AI Overviews have different interfaces — the source carousel and conversation UI of SGE differ from the AI Overviews citations panel. Advice specific to the SGE UI does not apply.</li>
          <li><strong>YMYL avoidance patterns from SGE.</strong> Google's handling of health and finance queries changed significantly between SGE and AI Overviews, following the inaccuracy incidents at launch. Query trigger rates for YMYL topics are different in the current product.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          The practical takeaway: treat SGE-era content as a historical foundation, validate every specific claim against current AI Overviews behaviour,
          and use current-product observation as your primary reference. Our
          <a href="/google-ai-overview-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">Google AI Overview Optimisation guide</a>
